        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Any business whose aggregate annual turnover (AATO) crossed Rs 5 crore in any financial year from 2017-18 onwards must generate e-invoices for B2B supplies, exports, deemed exports, and SEZ supplies. The mandate continues even if turnover later falls below the threshold."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the e-invoicing turnover threshold in 2026?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The threshold is Rs 5 crore aggregate annual turnover, in force since August 2023 under CBIC notifications. The threshold has progressively dropped from Rs 500 crore in 2020 to Rs 5 crore today, and policy direction suggests further reductions toward smaller businesses."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is e-invoicing the same as GST e-way bill?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. E-invoicing creates an Invoice Reference Number (IRN) for B2B tax invoices and feeds GSTR-1, while an e-way bill authorises movement of goods worth above Rs 50,000. They overlap when a B2B sale also moves goods, in which case the IRP can auto-generate the e-way bill from the e-invoice."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What happens if I do not generate an IRN?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Under Rule 48(5) of the CGST Rules an invoice issued without a valid IRN is not a legal tax invoice. Your customer cannot claim input tax credit, and penalties under Section 122 of the CGST Act can reach Rs 10,000 per invoice or the tax amount, whichever is higher, along with possible GSTIN suspension for repeated default."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can I generate an IRN after the invoice is sent to the customer?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "For businesses with turnover above Rs 100 crore, the IRP rejects invoices submitted more than 30 days after the invoice date. For other taxpayers the 30-day cap is not yet enforced but expected to be extended; best practice is to generate the IRN before issuing the invoice."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is e-invoicing required for B2C sales?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. E-invoicing applies only to B2B supplies, exports, deemed exports, and SEZ supplies. B2C invoices are out of scope. However, businesses with turnover above Rs 500 crore must print a dynamic QR code on B2C invoices under a separate rule."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How long does IRN generation take?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A valid invoice JSON submitted to the IRP via API typically returns an IRN and signed QR code within 1 to 3 seconds. Manual portal entry takes 2 to 5 minutes per invoice. Bulk Excel uploads process 100 invoices in roughly 30 to 60 seconds."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is the cost of e-invoicing software in India?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "The official GSTN portal at einvoice1.gst.gov.in is free for manual and limited bulk use. Paid SaaS billing tools start around Rs 2,999 per year (ClearTax, 2026 list price) and Tally Prime e-invoice add-on is around Rs 6,000 per year (Tally official, 2026). Custom ERP with built-in e-invoicing ranges from Rs 1.5 lakh upward depending on scope."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Can I migrate from manual portal to automated API?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes. Most businesses start on the free GSTN portal and shift to API once monthly volumes exceed 50 to 100 invoices. Migration involves choosing a registered GSP, generating API credentials, configuring your billing software, and running a sandbox parallel run before go-live."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Are exports and SEZ supplies subject to e-invoicing?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes. Both export invoices (with or without payment of IGST) and supplies to SEZ units or developers are within scope of e-invoicing once the business crosses the turnover threshold. The IRP supports specific document types and place-of-supply codes for these transactions."
        }
