<section class="faq-section" id="part-10" aria-labelledby="faq-heading">
  <h2 id="faq-heading">10. Frequently asked questions</h2>
  <p class="faq-sub">Quick answers to the questions most asked by Indian businesses entering the e-invoicing mandate in 2026.</p>
  <details class="faq-item">
    <summary>Who must comply with e-invoicing in 2026?</summary>
    <div class="faq-answer">Any business whose aggregate annual turnover (AATO) crossed Rs 5 crore in any financial year from 2017-18 onwards must generate e-invoices for B2B supplies, exports, deemed exports, and SEZ supplies. The mandate continues even if turnover later falls below the threshold.</div>
  </details>
  <details class="faq-item">
    <summary>What is the e-invoicing turnover threshold?</summary>
    <div class="faq-answer">The threshold is Rs 5 crore aggregate annual turnover, in force since August 2023 under CBIC notification 10/2023. The threshold has progressively dropped from Rs 500 crore in 2020 to Rs 5 crore today, and policy direction suggests further reductions toward smaller businesses.</div>
  </details>
  <details class="faq-item">
    <summary>Is e-invoicing the same as GST e-way bill?</summary>
    <div class="faq-answer">No. E-invoicing creates an Invoice Reference Number (IRN) for B2B tax invoices and feeds GSTR-1, while an e-way bill authorises movement of goods worth above Rs 50,000. They overlap when a B2B sale also moves goods, in which case the IRP can auto-generate the e-way bill from the e-invoice.</div>
  </details>
  <details class="faq-item">
    <summary>What happens if I don't generate an IRN?</summary>
    <div class="faq-answer">Under Rule 48(5) of the CGST Rules an invoice issued without a valid IRN is not a legal tax invoice. Your customer cannot claim input tax credit, and penalties under Section 122 of the CGST Act can reach Rs 10,000 per invoice or the tax amount, whichever is higher, along with possible GSTIN suspension for repeated default.</div>
  </details>
  <details class="faq-item">
    <summary>Can I generate an IRN after the invoice is sent to the customer?</summary>
    <div class="faq-answer">For businesses with turnover above Rs 100 crore the IRP rejects invoices submitted more than 30 days after the invoice date. For other taxpayers the 30-day cap is not yet enforced but expected to be extended. Best practice is to generate the IRN before issuing the invoice — the QR code must be on the printed copy.</div>
  </details>
  <details class="faq-item">
    <summary>Is e-invoicing required for B2C sales?</summary>
    <div class="faq-answer">No. E-invoicing applies only to B2B supplies, exports, deemed exports, and SEZ supplies. B2C invoices are out of scope. However, businesses with turnover above Rs 500 crore must print a dynamic QR code on B2C invoices under a separate rule.</div>
  </details>
  <details class="faq-item">
    <summary>How long does IRN generation take?</summary>
    <div class="faq-answer">A valid invoice JSON submitted to the IRP via API typically returns an IRN and signed QR code within 1 to 3 seconds. Manual portal entry takes 2 to 5 minutes per invoice. Bulk Excel uploads process 100 invoices in roughly 30 to 60 seconds.</div>
  </details>
  <details class="faq-item">
    <summary>What is the cost of e-invoicing software in India?</summary>
    <div class="faq-answer">The official GSTN portal at einvoice1.gst.gov.in is free for manual and limited bulk use. Paid SaaS billing tools start around Rs 2,999/year (ClearTax e-invoicing, 2026 list price) and Tally Prime e-invoice add-on is around Rs 6,000/year (Tally official, 2026). Custom ERP with built-in e-invoicing ranges from Rs 1.5 lakh upward depending on scope.</div>
  </details>
  <details class="faq-item">
    <summary>Can I migrate from manual portal to automated API?</summary>
    <div class="faq-answer">Yes. Most businesses start on the free GSTN portal and shift to API once monthly volumes exceed 50 to 100 invoices. Migration involves choosing a registered GSP, generating API credentials, configuring your billing software, and running a sandbox parallel run before go-live. Allow 2-3 weeks for a clean migration.</div>
  </details>
  <details class="faq-item">
    <summary>Are exports and SEZ supplies subject to e-invoicing?</summary>
    <div class="faq-answer">Yes. Both export invoices (with or without payment of IGST) and supplies to SEZ units or developers fall under the e-invoicing mandate once the business crosses the turnover threshold. The IRP supports specific document types and place-of-supply codes for these transactions; SEZ developers as recipients are exempt, but SEZ units as recipients are in scope.</div>
  </details>
</section>

